Date: Wed 16 Oct 2002
From: "Pablo Nart" <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source ICBirmingham online, Wed 16 Oct 2002 [edited]
<http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/0100news/0100localnews/page.cfm?objectid>

England: Hospital Outbreaks in the West Midlands
-------------------------------------------------
Hundreds of people have been struck by a sickness epidemic which has forced
the closure of at least 12 wards in hospitals across the West
Midlands. Nursing and residential homes for the elderly have also been hit
by the outbreak of viral gastroenteritis which is threatening to throw
hospital admissions into chaos. Four wards have already been closed to new
admissions at Walsall Manor Hospital while a further three have been shut
at Birmingham's City Hospital and Rowley Regis Hospital. Bosses at Sandwell
Hospital have so far quarantined one ward, along with New Cross Hospital in
Wolverhampton. Patients at Heartlands, Good Hope and Selly Oak hospitals
have also been struck down with the diarrhoea and sickness bug which is
thought to have been spreading for the past 2 weeks. John Rostill, chief
executive at Walsall Manor Hospital, said: "It puts more pressure on us
because we don't want to move the staff caring for patients with
gastroenteritis." West Midlands Ambulance Service was called in to help
struggling casualty units on Monday when City Hospital and a number of
Black Country hospitals closed their doors to emergency admissions for up
to an hour. Lorene Read, director of operations at Sandwell and West
Birmingham Hospitals NHS Trust, which runs City Hospital in Dudley Road,
said some staff had also been affected by the illness. "We're going to see
that start to impact on accident and emergency," she said. Dr John Kemm,
consultant in public health medicine for the Department of Health, said:
"People need to be extra careful about making sure everything they handle
is clean. They need to be particularly careful about washing their hands."
[By Paula Marsh, Evening Mail]
