ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[There is some confusion among clinicians regarding the naming of the
viruses associated with "Winter Vomiting Illness". The designation
"Norwalk-like viruses" was adopted by the International Committee on
Taxonomy of Viruses (ICTV) as the temporary genus name for a collection of
related caliciviruses associated with viral gastroenteritis. The genus
takes its name from the type species _Norwalk virus_, which was the first
of these viruses to be characterized in any detail. The Norwalk-like
viruses are now considered to be a coherent group and the formal genus name
_Norovirus_ was recently approved by the ICTV. It is likely that the short
duration of immunity following recovery and the variable incidence from
year-to-year are reflections of the antigenic and biological heterogeneity
of the noroviruses. Initially these viruses were associated with localized
food and water-borne outbreaks of gastroenteritis in North America, but in
recent years in Europe they have been associated with extensive outbreaks
of vomiting disease in institutional settings. It is unclear at present
whether this is due to genetic difference in the virus strains in
circulation or to other epidemiological factors. The above reports indicate
that outbreaks of "winter-vomiting " disease are being experienced in
hospitals throughout the length and breadth of the British Isles at the
present time. - Mod.CP]
